@startuml
!define AWSPuml https://raw.githubusercontent.com/awslabs/aws-icons-for-plantuml/v20.0/dist
!include AWSPuml/AWSCommon.puml

title High-Level Deployment Architecture (Insufficient Codebase Details)

skinparam shadowing false
skinparam componentStyle rectangle
skinparam wrapWidth 200

node "Deployment Environment\n(Cloud or On-Prem)" as env {
  node "Application Runtime" as runtime {
    artifact "App Service\n(technology unknown)" as app
  }

  database "Data Store\n(optional / unknown)" as db
  folder "Object Storage\n(optional / unknown)" as storage
}

actor "User / Client" as user

user --> app : HTTP(S)
app --> db : read/write (if used)
app --> storage : read/write (if used)

note right of app
Codebase contents could not be analyzed due to
path resolution/access issues.
Languages, frameworks, and dependencies are unknown.
This diagram is a safe placeholder architecture.
end note

@enduml

architecture_description:
## High-level architecture (based on limited available analysis)

Because the repository contents could not be inspected (path resolution/access issues), the programming languages, frameworks, dependencies, and concrete infrastructure needs are unknown. The architecture below is therefore a **safe placeholder** that represents the most common deployable shape for an application.

### Components
- **User / Client**: Browser, mobile app, or another service calling the system.
- **App Service (technology unknown)**: The primary deployable unit (e.g., a web API, backend service, or monolith) running in an **Application Runtime** (VM, container, Kubernetes, PaaS, etc.).
- **Data Store (optional / unknown)**: A database or persistence layer the app may use (SQL/NoSQL).
- **Object Storage (optional / unknown)**: Blob/file storage the app may use for artifacts, uploads, logs, or media.

### Relationships
- The **User/Client** communicates with the **App Service** over **HTTP(S)**.
- The **App Service** may read/write to a **Data Store**.
- The **App Service** may read/write to **Object Storage**.

### Whatâ€™s missing / how to refine
To produce a technology-accurate deployment diagram, the analysis would need access to repository contents (e.g., package manifests, Dockerfiles, IaC files, CI/CD configs). With that, the diagram can be updated to include specific runtimes (Docker/K8s), concrete databases (PostgreSQL, DynamoDB, etc.), queues/caches, and external integrations.
